## Archetype Implications for Intervention Design

Different clusters require different policy responses:
- High-density, high-frequency clusters benefit most from **frequency enhancement and network integration** — marginal improvements on already-good infrastructure
- Low-density, isolated clusters require **structural interventions** — new routes, DRT schemes, or community transport — since frequency enhancement is meaningless where no service exists
- Mixed-deprivation clusters with adequate physical access but poor service quality benefit from **operating hours extension and weekend service restoration**

One-size-fits-all interventions (e.g., blanket frequency targets) will systematically under-serve the clusters that most need tailored solutions.

## Targeting Recommendations

Cluster membership provides a targeting variable for BSIP funding allocation. LTAs can use the cluster an LSOA belongs to as a first-pass filter for intervention type, then apply deprivation and population weighting to prioritise within clusters.

*Methodology: {{ entity_type }} clustered using HDBSCAN algorithm (density-based, no assumption of spherical clusters). Features normalised before clustering. Cluster descriptions generated from mean feature values per cluster. Source data: BODS GTFS, IMD 2025, Census 2021.*
